resource.chars: And many kinds of venison,
Captured by force through running hunting dogs,
Stags, deer, rabbits, wild boars,
Which live in these woods,
And all kinds of good venison.
There was an abundance of fish,
The best of the whole region:
Sturgeons, salmon and plaice,
Congers, sea bass, porpoises, brill,
Turbots, red mullets and large codfish,
Fatty mackerels and large hakes,
Fresh herrings and smelt,
And so many other fish of the sea
As if one had attempted to sow them.
There were also many sorts,
Fish from ponds and from rivers,
Each one prepared with great attention,
According to its nature,
With green sauce or with cameline sauce.
There were pikes in a gelatinous sauce,
Large sea lampreys prepared in the same way,
And roaches and breams afterwards
In a different preparation.
And then trout pâté,
Chubs and roasted carps,
Marinated in verjuice,
And large eels in a pastry
And roasted in the fire.
Sticklebacks in a “chaudume” sauce,
As is the custom
Of cooks who know the rules
For preparing them. There were tenches
Which are called “upside down.”
There were waffles and wafers,
Choux pastry, tarts and flans,
Cheese tarts in large heaps,
Apples in spices, cakes with cream,
Crêpes, doughnuts and fried croquettes.
There were good and precious wines,
Very delicious to drink:
Some were spiced with zedoary, some with rose and other flowers,
Well colored wines from Gascony,
From Montpellier and La Rochelle,
And sweet wines and wine from Castille,
From Beaune and from Saint-Pourçain,
Which rich people consider healthful,
From Saint-Gengoux and from Navarre,
From the vineyard called La Barre,
From Spain, from Anjou, from Orléans,
From Auxerre and from the region around Laon,
And from Saint-Jean and the Beauvaisis,
French wine and wine from nearby places.
There was wine with honey and spices and good claret.
The most powerful and the most richly dressed
Ate the most gluttonously.
They devoured the wines.
There was a cook who had devoted all of his attention
To making a dish of a very different sort,
Without delaying.
He made it quickly, fresh and appetizing,
With a sauce so spicy
That everyone is eager to drink.
It was served between the roasts and the dessert.
It was tasty and delicious, but
Everyone immediately calls out for drink so much
That a big barrel of wine must be brought up
Into the hall.
Everyone, when they see it, laughs and jumps.
The barrel is called Shame:
Excess draws and gives so much from it
That she cannot be called avaricious.
One does not wait to wash up
In order to drink; but rather drinks in big gulps.
In this way, they receive both shame and joy.
The fried plate I mentioned above
Was made of sins against nature
And of all different kinds of other sins
Through which the situation has changed
To the disadvantage of the good, there where Fauvel resides,
Who attacks and overthrows everything.
This is the kind of food that people
Who are slanderers must eat.
This is what people who have power
Out of nothing [?] are like—and even worse.
Debauchery, who works with spices,
Has a very joyful expression there.
These are strong spices, strong sweets
Composed of the sin of envy,
Ardent covetousness and theft,
Of pleasure for which everyone thirsts,
Which she distributes and delivers everywhere
Very generously and without any discussion,
And everyone licks his beard.
Whoever takes any has a mouth so dry
That he must drink immediately
And says: “How is it possible that wine does not come?”
Then the cupbearer appears, as well as Drunkenness,
And each one pours and fills the cups generously
And has some poured for each table,
Both in the length of the room and the width,
With wine in such a great quantity
That everyone has complete freedom
To get drunk gluttonously.
Even Excess, in order to meet demand,
Opens the barrel with her mouth.
Drunkenness stands so closely to her
That the barrel will soon be empty!
Everyone exerts great pains in drinking.
They will always have drunk shame
And spread it everywhere inside,
Except near the very gracious
Ladies who are the opposite of the Vices
Which were discussed above.
They have a very modest behavior and are
Wise, beautiful, pleasant,
They are good listeners and better at keeping quiet,
Well educated in honor and goodness.
They were seated together.
This filthy and porcine people
Does not pay attention to them, for
From all sides the crowd is so thick
That people cannot see each other,
And because everyone works
At putting shame in his belly.
The ladies whose gaze was directed towards God
Did not behave in this way ever.
They abstained from the food.
They looked around modestly.
Abstinence and Sobriety,
Temperance and Purity
And Moderation, who do not bend,
Serve them and cut up slices.
